Wash and dry produce.

Thinly slice @mini cucumber{1}(thinly sliced into half-moons). Roughly chop
@cilantro{1/4%ounce}(roughly chopped, including tender stems).

Pat @pork chops{10%ounce} dry; very thinly slice crosswise. Season all over
with @garlic powder{1%teaspoon}, @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Drizzle @cooking oil{1%teaspoon} in a hot #large pan{}. Cook pork, stirring
occasionally, until browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}. Turn off heat
and stir in @sweet Thai chili sauce{1%ounce} until pork is coated.

Meanwhile, in a #medium microwave-safe bowl{}, mix cucumber, half the carrots,
@shredded carrots{4%ounce}, @rice wine vinegar{5%teaspoon}, @sugar{1/2%teaspoon},
and a pinch of @salt{} (all the carrots and 1 tsp sugar for 4). Microwave
~{30%seconds}. Set aside to pickle, stirring occasionally.

Halve and toast @demi-baguette{2} until golden using a #toaster{}.

In a #large bowl{}, toss @mixed greens{2%ounce}, @sliced almonds{1/2%ounce},
and @sesame dressing{1.5%ounce}.

Drain liquid from pickled veggies; stir in cilantro.

Spread cut sides of baguettes with as much @spicy mayo{4%tablespoon} as you
like. Fill with pork, @crispy fried onions{1}, about half the pickled veggies,
and as much @Sriracha{2%teaspoon} as you like.

Serve sandwiches and salad with remaining pickled veggies.

> Tonight's dinner features our spin on a Vietnamese banh mi sandwich. Quick-cooking,
> flavorful, and tossed in a sweet Thai chili sauce, thinly sliced pork makes a perfect
> sandwich-stuffer. It's piled high with a sesame-dressed green salad plus
> crunchy almonds, quick pickled carrots and cukes, and loaded into toasty baguettes
> spread with spicy mayo. Top with crispy fried onions and as much Sriracha as
> you like, and serve with extra salad and pickles on the side – all this in just
> a quick 15 minutes!